<h4>
    More facts on thermal equilibrium:
</h4>

<p>
    Look around the room you are in.
    Right now, just about everything in the room is in <strong>thermal equilibrium</strong>!
    Any objects that have been round each other for a long time are in thermal equilibrium.
</p>

<p>
    There are some exceptions: anything that is being continuously heated or cooled.
    This includes:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Yourself, because your body burns energy to maintain a temperature of 37&#176;C
        (or 98&#176;F).
    </li>
    <li>
        A computer, or any electrical device that generates heat
        (although they generate much less heat than in the past, because people
        have continually been generating more efficient appliances).
    </li>
    <li>
        Something near a window, if the temperature outside is much different than the temperature
        inside and/or sunlight is coming in.
    </li>
    <li>
        Water in an open container:
        water is usually cooler than the environment around it due to a process called <emph>evaporation</emph>.
        However, for evaporation to happen, water must be in an open container.
    </li>
</ul>

